ivacy fence. <img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/DCjr08Il.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\nInitially the idea was to pour a concrete pad for the Airstream to rest on. But during the clearing and tilling of the yard we found a significant number of old bricks in decent condition that would work just as well. Not to mention they would give the spot a bit of charm, who doesn\'t like re-purposed bricks? Behold the aftermath of junk stone and brick.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/pzG7Ugll.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">So, a spot was measured, 6ft by 8ft plot for the bricks to be laid. Tilled it, smoothed it, stomped it and started putting the clay down. Turns out there was roughly a third of the bricks required for the job, but bricks are not hard to come by from many of the crumbling buildings in south St. Louis. Below are a couple pictures of the unfinished pad, which will be completed, leveled and sanded in a future post. The trailer is getting closer to being in position and almost ready for the pulling and striping of the innards. <img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/fzr4TMql.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/d0JO7JPl.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>','Breaking ground.','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-v1','','','2014-10-29 14:00:33','2014-10-29 14:00:33','',27,'http://localhost/?p=70',0,'revision','',0),(71,1,'2014-10-29 14:01:24','2014-10-29 14:01:24','Before I get started on the trailer itself, it needs a nice bed to rest on.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">First, to choose a location. Considering the best use of the yard, as well as the place easiest to maneuver the Airstream into, the south side seemed best. This would allow the awning to be used in its full glory (pics eventually) across the yard, and the trailer would separate the two properties, functioning like a privacy fence. <img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/DCjr08Il.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\nInitially the idea was to pour a concrete pad for the Airstream to rest on. But during the clearing and tilling of the yard we found a significant number of old bricks in decent condition that would work just as well. Not to mention they would give the spot a bit of charm, who doesn\'t like re-purposed bricks? Behold the aftermath of junk stone and brick.\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/pzG7Ugll.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">So, a spot was measured, 6ft by 8ft plot for the bricks to be laid. Tilled it, smoothed it, stomped it and started putting the clay down. Turns out there was roughly a third of the bricks required for the job, but bricks are not hard to come by from many of the crumbling buildings in south St. Louis. Below are a couple pictures of the unfinished pad, which will be completed, leveled and sanded in a future post. The trailer is getting closer to being in position and almost ready for the pulling and striping of the innards. <img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/fzr4TMql.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/d0JO7JPl.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>','Breaking ground.','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-v1','','','2014-10-29 14:01:24','2014-10-29 14:01:24','',27,'http://localhost/?p=71',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2014-11-03 18:16:00','2014-11-03 18:16:00','This weekend the kitchen was karate kicked to oblivion.\r\n\r\nDemo was started in the Airstream this weekend. The kitchen was falling apart, so it was the first to go. Things that could be saved were, but with the condition of the cabinetry, that ment mostly fasteners, trim, and screws.\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/ghQ3hOgl.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nThe sink was in pretty good condition and was easily removed.\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/wj4IuYjl.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nBut the two main appliances, the oven/stove and the heater were also salvaged.\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/BVBWFJkl.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nI also pined at the original control pannel for the trailer, and its solid state awesomeness.\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/gB01IV0l.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nAs I came to a stopping point as it was clear some consult was needed regarding what to keep and what to trash. \r\nAll and all it was a pretty light day. Now I am itching to keep pulling things out of the trailer, hopefully after talking with a more knowledgeable person.\r\n\r\n  ','That kitchen had to go.','','publish','open','open','','that-kitchen-had-to-go','','','2014-11-03 18:16:00','2014-11-03 18:16:00','',0,'http://localhost/?p=72',0,'post','',0),(73,1,'2014-11-03 18:14:37','2014-11-03 18:14:37','This weekend the kitchen was karate kicked to oblivion.\r\n\r\nDemo was started in the Airstream this weekend. The kitchen was falling apart, so it was the first to go. Things that could be saved were, but with the condition of the cabinetry, that ment mostly fasteners, trim, and screws.\r\n<img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/wj4IuYjl.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nThe sink was in pretty good condition and was easily removed.\r\n<img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/ghQ3hOgl.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nBut the two main appliances, the oven/stove and the heater were also salvaged.\r\n<img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/BVBWFJkl.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nI also pined at the original control pannel for the trailer, and its solid state awesomeness.\r\n<img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/gB01IV0l.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\nAs I came to a stopping point as it was clear some consult was needed regarding what to keep and what to trash. \r\nAll and all it was a pretty light day. Now I am itching to keep pulling things out of the trailer, hopefully after talking with a more knowledgeable person.\r\n\r\n  ','That kitchen had to go.','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-v1','','','201